495
00:29:15.292 --> 00:29:19.112
And obviously, mutations in PI3-kinase, they are scattered all over this

496
00:29:19.192 --> 00:29:23.132
large holoenzyme, with quite poor understanding

497
00:29:23.232 --> 00:29:25.792
of most of their mechanisms of action

498
00:29:26.612 --> 00:29:29.372
and how they might be shaping the response to

499
00:29:29.452 --> 00:29:31.472
PI3-kinase-targeting inhibitors.

500
00:29:33.272 --> 00:29:37.092
So to understand PI3-kinase, one has to kind of understand the architecture of this

501
00:29:37.172 --> 00:29:40.452
rather large holoenzyme, which is quite complicated.

502
00:29:40.512 --> 00:29:44.032
It's a constitutive heterodimer between the catalytic subunit

503
00:29:44.112 --> 00:29:48.052
p110 and the regulatory subunit p85 that

504
00:29:48.252 --> 00:29:51.182
are in this very intimate interaction with each other,

505
00:29:51.812 --> 00:29:54.932
primarily driving autoinhibition of the enzyme.

506
00:29:55.632 --> 00:29:59.512
Ras binds to the Ras-binding domain of the catalytic subunit, and

507
00:29:59.552 --> 00:30:03.052
the phosphorylated tails of receptor tyrosine

508
00:30:03.132 --> 00:30:06.912
kinases engage SH2 domains in the regulatory subunit.

509
00:30:08.732 --> 00:30:12.552
As you can see, so there are two SH2 domains, NSH2

510
00:30:12.612 --> 00:30:15.752
domain, and CSH2 domain. They're connected by this

511
00:30:16.852 --> 00:30:19.992
deceivingly called ISH2 linker domain.

512
00:30:20.032 --> 00:30:23.392
It's actually a long coiled coil. It's not an SH2 domain.

513
00:30:25.422 --> 00:30:28.992
All structures which are

514
00:30:29.452 --> 00:30:33.412
currently solved in PDB of PI3-kinase show it in the

515
00:30:33.452 --> 00:30:37.392
auto-inhibited form. And in this form, only two domains

516
00:30:37.432 --> 00:30:41.072
of a regulatory subunit, the N-terminal SH2 domain and this linker

517
00:30:41.152 --> 00:30:44.392
domain, are resolved and show this really strong

518
00:30:44.452 --> 00:30:45.212
inhibition.

519
00:30:46.632 --> 00:30:50.232
PI3-kinase is known to be activated by binding to phosphorylated

520
00:30:50.312 --> 00:30:53.252
tails and by being recruited to the membrane.

521
00:30:54.032 --> 00:30:57.792
But there are-When we started this project, there were

522
00:30:57.872 --> 00:31:01.552
no structures of PI3 kinase in the active conformation, which was

523
00:31:01.592 --> 00:31:03.712
quite mind-boggling to us.

524
00:31:04.732 --> 00:31:08.712
So out of all, more than 100 structures available, zero

525
00:31:08.772 --> 00:31:09.972
are in the active

526
00:31:10.852 --> 00:31:14.672
form, and we hypothesized that this might be because nobody ever actually

527
00:31:14.752 --> 00:31:18.432
tried to solve the structure of PI3 kinase in the context of the

528
00:31:18.492 --> 00:31:21.932
membrane, which is really where it becomes activated when it

529
00:31:21.992 --> 00:31:24.272
encounters its substrate PIP2.

530
00:31:25.822 --> 00:31:29.732
So we thought this would be an interesting angle to try to see

531
00:31:29.772 --> 00:31:33.252
if we can tackle this holy grail in PI3 kinase

532
00:31:33.592 --> 00:31:34.272
activation.

533
00:31:35.612 --> 00:31:39.172
And, the reason why we are really interested in it is because the

534
00:31:39.232 --> 00:31:42.972
expertise of my lab is really studying her receptor signaling.

535
00:31:43.032 --> 00:31:46.492
And in the context of this very important oncogenic subunit,

536
00:31:46.892 --> 00:31:48.532
HER2, HER3 heterodimer,

537
00:31:49.512 --> 00:31:53.172
HER3 receptor, which is actually catalytically inactive, is a

538
00:31:53.352 --> 00:31:56.852
super scaffold of PI3 kinase. It has six

539
00:31:56.872 --> 00:32:00.792
phosphorylation sites, which are phosphorylated by HER2, that create

540
00:32:00.802 --> 00:32:04.432
this very interesting and puzzling multivalent mode of recruitment of

541
00:32:04.492 --> 00:32:06.812
PI3 kinase to the membrane.

542
00:32:08.072 --> 00:32:08.432
And

543
00:32:09.692 --> 00:32:13.612
we still fully don't understand what it does to PI3 kinase signaling and

544
00:32:13.672 --> 00:32:17.532
why this is important, and we think that our recent work might shed some

545
00:32:17.672 --> 00:32:21.572
light on why multivalency might be making a difference in

546
00:32:21.632 --> 00:32:24.292
regulating amplitude of PI3 kinase signaling.

547
00:32:26.272 --> 00:32:30.222
Another reason why we were interested in PI3 kinase was

548
00:32:30.232 --> 00:32:33.732
because of our collaboration with Navan Krogan and Jennifer Grandis at

549
00:32:33.792 --> 00:32:37.612
UCSF, and Silvio Gatkin at UCSD, who did a very

550
00:32:37.672 --> 00:32:41.232
interesting experiment in which they looked at the associated

551
00:32:41.392 --> 00:32:44.712
proteomes of individual oncogenic PI3 kinase

552
00:32:44.812 --> 00:32:45.592
mutations

553
00:32:46.532 --> 00:32:50.472
and noticed that they slightly differ, and different mutants tend to

554
00:32:50.792 --> 00:32:52.852
bind to different proteome in a cell.

555
00:32:53.352 --> 00:32:57.132
And there is this very interesting red cluster, which you can see here, which when

556
00:32:57.152 --> 00:33:00.802
you zoom in, you will see that certain mutants really

557
00:33:00.832 --> 00:33:04.532
enrich these proteins. And one of these proteins is HER3,

558
00:33:05.892 --> 00:33:09.852
and the other ones is Gab1 and IRS1, which are also proteins

559
00:33:09.892 --> 00:33:12.822
that are multivalent recruiters of PI3 kinase.

560
00:33:13.352 --> 00:33:17.152
So there is something interesting between this ability to bind a

561
00:33:17.192 --> 00:33:21.002
lot of subunits of PI3 kinase and oncogenic potential of

562
00:33:21.032 --> 00:33:24.592
PI3 kinase mutants, which we thought was very interesting.

563
00:33:26.272 --> 00:33:30.132
So how do you start this? So we thought, well, in order to really finally

564
00:33:30.232 --> 00:33:33.972
look at PI3 kinase in the active conformation, we should provide all the

565
00:33:34.352 --> 00:33:37.392
things that it needs to become activated.

566
00:33:37.452 --> 00:33:40.932
And there is sort of a menu of things that do that, the

567
00:33:40.992 --> 00:33:44.412
activating inputs like RAS and phosphorylated tails,

568
00:33:44.812 --> 00:33:47.872
perhaps its substrate PIP2, and of course, the membrane.

569
00:33:49.152 --> 00:33:52.872
In our lab, we use lipid nanodiscs, which are really

570
00:33:52.952 --> 00:33:56.492
small artificial membrane bilayer pieces that we

571
00:33:56.612 --> 00:33:57.512
use for

572
00:33:58.492 --> 00:34:02.312
reconstitution of proteins at the membrane and use cryo-EM to

573
00:34:02.372 --> 00:34:05.632
look at the structures of these membrane-associated

574
00:34:05.732 --> 00:34:06.372
complexes.

575
00:34:07.412 --> 00:34:10.453
So we started by purifying full-length PI3 kinase and

576
00:34:11.692 --> 00:34:15.572
putting it on the membrane of the lipid nanodiscs, and that was

577
00:34:15.672 --> 00:34:19.412
actually a huge failure. PI3 kinase really didn't want to associate with lipid

578
00:34:19.453 --> 00:34:20.192
nanodiscs.

579
00:34:20.993 --> 00:34:24.832
But what really changed was when we premixed PI3 kinase

580
00:34:24.892 --> 00:34:28.412
with farnesylated K-RAS that we have gotten from

581
00:34:28.533 --> 00:34:30.473
NCI for the RAS initiative.

582
00:34:31.513 --> 00:34:35.033
And when we formed the complex with K-RAS, now this

583
00:34:35.132 --> 00:34:36.252
farnesyl moiety

584
00:34:37.252 --> 00:34:40.912
presumably drove this complex to the membrane, and we were able to

585
00:34:40.953 --> 00:34:44.752
form stable complexes and do some cryo-EM analysis of

586
00:34:44.792 --> 00:34:48.513
these complexes. But we were stuck at relatively low

587
00:34:48.553 --> 00:34:51.033
resolution, so we couldn't really resolve anything.

588
00:34:51.572 --> 00:34:55.432
What ended up being a very interesting development

589
00:34:55.892 --> 00:34:59.632
in this process was getting our hands on the molecular

590
00:34:59.752 --> 00:35:02.412
glue, which I'm sure Eric will appreciate.

591
00:35:02.672 --> 00:35:05.812
It was given to us by Frank McCormick at UCSF.

592
00:35:06.272 --> 00:35:09.772
He has been developing it in collaboration with other groups.

593
00:35:10.452 --> 00:35:14.412
This glue binds to the RAS binding domain of PI3 kinase and to

594
00:35:14.451 --> 00:35:18.392
RAS and brings them together in a stable conformation.

595
00:35:18.732 --> 00:35:22.612
This allowed us to get a high-resolution structure of this entire

596
00:35:22.692 --> 00:35:25.712
complex at the surface of the lipid nanodisc.

597
00:35:26.672 --> 00:35:30.232
And this is what I'm showing you. Here with K-RAS being in orange

598
00:35:30.712 --> 00:35:34.432
and the catalytic subunit in blue with ABD

599
00:35:34.472 --> 00:35:38.412
domain in that subunit in lighter blue and the portion of the

600
00:35:38.432 --> 00:35:40.932
regulatory subunit in gray.

601
00:35:41.772 --> 00:35:45.602
We couldn't really see the surface of the nanodisc, but when you look at the

602
00:35:45.612 --> 00:35:48.932
low-pass filtered map, we can see the nanodisc.

603
00:35:49.032 --> 00:35:52.672
It's very curiously oriented at an angle to this

604
00:35:53.712 --> 00:35:57.572
hollow enzyme. And you can see that the farnesyl moiety of

605
00:35:57.612 --> 00:36:01.452
K-RAS is making an interaction, kind of inserting itself into this

606
00:36:01.552 --> 00:36:04.492
lipid nanodisc right here, which was interesting.

607
00:36:05.982 --> 00:36:09.532
We are very excited because this data set allowed us

608
00:36:09.572 --> 00:36:13.412
to analyze different classes that allowed us to actually

609
00:36:13.432 --> 00:36:16.832
build a trajectory of PI3 kinase being

610
00:36:16.932 --> 00:36:20.632
increasingly more activated. And what you can

611
00:36:20.772 --> 00:36:24.592
hopefully appreciate is the disappearance of the gray and light

612
00:36:24.652 --> 00:36:28.392
blue density as we move from class one to class three, which are these

613
00:36:28.412 --> 00:36:32.132
auto-inhibitory domains that keep PI3 kinase in an inactive

614
00:36:32.272 --> 00:36:36.232
state. And the slow dissociation of the inhibitory

615
00:36:36.272 --> 00:36:40.212
subunits have never been seen before in the solution structures of PI3

616
00:36:40.252 --> 00:36:41.932
kinase that were obtained before.

617
00:36:43.352 --> 00:36:47.302
So to us, what that meant was that bringing PI3 kinase

618
00:36:47.352 --> 00:36:51.312
to the membrane allowed it to peel off these auto-inhibitory domains and started

619
00:36:51.352 --> 00:36:52.612
becoming more

620
00:36:52.732 --> 00:36:56.720
active.Despite

621
00:36:56.740 --> 00:37:00.440
the fact that it seemed more active, the

622
00:37:00.520 --> 00:37:04.180
active site of PI3 kinase actually was quite far away from the

623
00:37:04.220 --> 00:37:08.020
membrane surface, and that worried us a little bit and told us that there is

624
00:37:08.160 --> 00:37:11.880
something that still blocks PI3 kinase from adopting a fully active

625
00:37:11.960 --> 00:37:12.880
conformation.

626
00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:17.620
And that thing seemed to be a rather mysterious extra

627
00:37:17.680 --> 00:37:21.300
density that was kind of buttressing between PI3 kinase and a lipid

628
00:37:21.360 --> 00:37:22.040
nanodisk.

629
00:37:22.960 --> 00:37:26.840
And we really didn't get to a high resolution in this region of the structure to

630
00:37:26.900 --> 00:37:30.640
know exactly what it is. But by using AlphaFold, we have a pretty

631
00:37:30.680 --> 00:37:34.510
good guess that what it might be is actually never seen before,

632
00:37:34.890 --> 00:37:38.460
C-terminal SH2 domain of regulatory subunit.

633
00:37:39.190 --> 00:37:42.800
This is really interesting because our structure suggests that this domain

634
00:37:42.900 --> 00:37:46.280
directly interacts with lipids at the membrane,

635
00:37:46.860 --> 00:37:50.580
and there are actually, as you might all know, SH2 domain

636
00:37:50.620 --> 00:37:52.840
interacts with phosphorylated tyrosines.

637
00:37:53.400 --> 00:37:56.680
But there is actually a lot of studies showing that some SH2 domains

638
00:37:57.260 --> 00:38:00.940
make pretty good interaction with phospholipids and including

639
00:38:01.020 --> 00:38:04.880
CSH2 domain of PI3 kinase. So it seems to us that this

640
00:38:04.940 --> 00:38:08.780
interaction might be an additional check that PI3 kinase might

641
00:38:08.800 --> 00:38:12.660
be making before it gets fully activated that needs to be

642
00:38:12.700 --> 00:38:16.420
released for activation. So what can release this check?

643
00:38:17.440 --> 00:38:21.200
Well, we figured that what might help is actually if we include a

644
00:38:21.340 --> 00:38:24.940
substrate of PI3 kinase in a lipid nanodisk, and we

645
00:38:24.960 --> 00:38:28.740
added PIP2 to our lipid mixture. And when we solved the

646
00:38:28.840 --> 00:38:32.240
structure of this complex on the PIP2-containing nanodisks,

647
00:38:32.760 --> 00:38:36.750
now we saw that the entire holoenzyme reoriented itself and

648
00:38:36.940 --> 00:38:40.670
really docked into the lipid bilayer and made very, very

649
00:38:40.720 --> 00:38:42.880
intimate interactions with the lipid bilayer.

650
00:38:44.140 --> 00:38:47.600
That was really interesting and exciting and particularly,

651
00:38:48.100 --> 00:38:51.040
consequential for the active site of PI3 kinase.

652
00:38:51.160 --> 00:38:54.780
I didn't really tell you much about it, not to overload you with details.

653
00:38:54.900 --> 00:38:58.680
I just want you to pay attention to this yellow K12

654
00:38:58.740 --> 00:39:02.680
region, which is a helical region, predicted to be helical, although

655
00:39:02.780 --> 00:39:06.640
had never been seen to be helical in any structures

656
00:39:06.700 --> 00:39:08.320
of PI3 kinase so far.

657
00:39:09.720 --> 00:39:13.460
We really don't know that because we've never had structures of PI3

658
00:39:13.500 --> 00:39:15.440
kinase in the active conformation.

659
00:39:16.400 --> 00:39:20.180
So when you compare a structure of this region in the inactive

660
00:39:20.320 --> 00:39:24.200
state, shown here on the left in this class one, and in

661
00:39:24.240 --> 00:39:28.080
our PIP2 structure, you see that this helix now

662
00:39:28.160 --> 00:39:32.020
becomes a true helix, and it swings all the way 180

663
00:39:32.080 --> 00:39:35.680
degrees in our PIP2-engaged holoenzyme

664
00:39:35.760 --> 00:39:39.720
structure. And this is accompanied by the conformational change

665
00:39:39.800 --> 00:39:43.360
in the activation lobe. And what this allows actually

666
00:39:43.460 --> 00:39:47.240
is to capture a substrate of PI3 kinase in the active

667
00:39:47.320 --> 00:39:50.960
site. This is the first time this has been seen

668
00:39:52.140 --> 00:39:52.260
in

669
00:39:54.020 --> 00:39:57.840
structures of PI3 kinase. Literally in our complex, PI3

670
00:39:57.860 --> 00:40:00.560
kinase grabs PIP2 from a nanodisk and

671
00:40:01.640 --> 00:40:03.820
interacts with it in its active site.

672
00:40:05.440 --> 00:40:09.320
So this helix, the swinging of the helix 180 degrees is really

673
00:40:09.380 --> 00:40:12.240
essential for activation and coordination of the lipid.

674
00:40:12.940 --> 00:40:16.500
But what this made us really excited about is this

675
00:40:16.740 --> 00:40:20.440
most common oncogenic mutation in PI3 kinase, histidine

676
00:40:20.480 --> 00:40:23.899
1047, which is mutated in one-third of human

677
00:40:23.980 --> 00:40:27.600
cancers to an arginine. And we always knew that this

678
00:40:27.660 --> 00:40:31.620
histidine is at this hinge region

679
00:40:31.680 --> 00:40:33.740
right before helix 12 starts.

680
00:40:34.960 --> 00:40:38.740
And what we think is happening is that what a mutation of the

681
00:40:38.800 --> 00:40:42.580
histidine, which is really essential for keeping helix 12 in an active

682
00:40:42.620 --> 00:40:45.630
state through the interaction with this tryptophan 1051,

683
00:40:46.420 --> 00:40:50.130
this interaction is disrupted by an arginine mutation,

684
00:40:50.620 --> 00:40:54.550
allowing swinging of the helix and adopting this active conformation,

685
00:40:54.640 --> 00:40:55.680
perhaps

686
00:40:56.620 --> 00:41:00.220
more readily than in the wild-type enzyme, driving

687
00:41:00.540 --> 00:41:02.840
oncogenic activation of PI3 kinase.

688
00:41:04.120 --> 00:41:07.960
And lastly, what was really exciting to us is that this extra

689
00:41:08.060 --> 00:41:12.020
density that we see for this mysterious C-terminal SH2 domain

690
00:41:12.480 --> 00:41:15.720
actually is exactly where the active

691
00:41:15.780 --> 00:41:17.700
conformation of helix 12

692
00:41:19.960 --> 00:41:22.120
is. So what we think is really

693
00:41:22.920 --> 00:41:26.260
happening is that the C-terminal SH2 domain, this

694
00:41:26.300 --> 00:41:30.200
location between the membrane and the holoenzyme, is a real

695
00:41:30.240 --> 00:41:33.700
auto-inhibitory step that provides additional check to

696
00:41:33.740 --> 00:41:37.680
prevent PI3 kinase from adopting an active conformation when

697
00:41:37.720 --> 00:41:38.940
it doesn't have to do it.

698
00:41:41.280 --> 00:41:45.160
And lastly, what we did is we added one more component

699
00:41:45.230 --> 00:41:49.180
to our complex, which is phosphorylated tails from the

700
00:41:49.220 --> 00:41:52.880
HER3 receptor, and really starts with a very simple

701
00:41:53.060 --> 00:41:56.400
component, which is just two tyrosine sites,

702
00:41:56.440 --> 00:41:58.160
phosphorylated tyrosine sites.

703
00:41:59.220 --> 00:42:00.250
And when we did that,

704
00:42:01.440 --> 00:42:03.300
and we got two different classes of

705
00:42:04.140 --> 00:42:07.280
complexes. One of them was very similar to our

706
00:42:07.320 --> 00:42:11.190
PIP2-only reconstruction, where PI3 kinase was really

707
00:42:11.220 --> 00:42:15.200
engaged with a lipid bilayer and fully active.

708
00:42:15.220 --> 00:42:19.040
But another portion of the particles formed this really interesting

709
00:42:19.200 --> 00:42:23.000
complex that migrated to the edge of a nanodisk with two

710
00:42:23.040 --> 00:42:26.800
KRAS molecules inserting their farnesyl moieties

711
00:42:26.840 --> 00:42:30.420
into the lipid bilayer, promoting dimerization of the

712
00:42:30.460 --> 00:42:34.240
entire PI3 kinase holoenzyme, something that has never been seen

713
00:42:34.300 --> 00:42:34.840
before.

714
00:42:36.530 --> 00:42:40.500
This dimer has really a large dimerization interface,

715
00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:44.800
and what it does, it completely prevents

716
00:42:45.020 --> 00:42:48.440
reassembly of auto-inhibited state of PI3 kinase.

717
00:42:48.480 --> 00:42:52.440
You can see here our dimer structure is overlaid on an auto-inhibited

718
00:42:52.660 --> 00:42:56.640
structure of PI3 kinase, and you can see that association of this gray

719
00:42:56.660 --> 00:43:00.240
and light blue domain is impossible if PI3

720
00:43:00.280 --> 00:43:03.800
kinase dimerizes. So we think what happens is that

721
00:43:04.260 --> 00:43:08.250
this dimericPreviously not observed state

722
00:43:08.290 --> 00:43:12.230
of PI3-kinase is really a fully activated state that

723
00:43:12.830 --> 00:43:16.750
is less likely to equilibrate back to an auto-inhibited state.

724
00:43:17.890 --> 00:43:21.510
So to sum up what we have learned from all this

725
00:43:21.570 --> 00:43:23.680
work for PI3-kinase activation,

726
00:43:24.930 --> 00:43:28.700
we think that we can propose a trajectory for how it is activated.

727
00:43:29.190 --> 00:43:32.090
In the auto-inhibited states, it's fully in the cytosol.

728
00:43:33.350 --> 00:43:36.490
It can get to the membrane, but in the absence of

729
00:43:37.630 --> 00:43:41.530
fully activated components, the C-terminal SH2 domain

730
00:43:41.570 --> 00:43:45.240
might be preventing its engagement with the substrate by blocking,

731
00:43:45.650 --> 00:43:49.010
really binding fully to the membrane bilayer.

732
00:43:49.930 --> 00:43:51.530
Now, with the help of Ras,

733
00:43:53.630 --> 00:43:57.510
and the presence of PIP2, now PI3-kinase can engage fully

734
00:43:57.590 --> 00:44:01.339
in the membrane. And with the presence of phosphorylated tails,

735
00:44:01.410 --> 00:44:04.890
which probably should be drawn even earlier because they really provide this

736
00:44:04.930 --> 00:44:08.770
initial recruitment, what happens, you switch to this state where

737
00:44:08.810 --> 00:44:12.790
PI3-kinase might be adopting this active dimer

738
00:44:13.430 --> 00:44:17.110
that now is less likely to equilibrate back to the

739
00:44:17.130 --> 00:44:20.850
auto-inhibited confirmation. And we think that the

740
00:44:20.890 --> 00:44:24.310
